        },
        {
            "id": 1,
            "parent": 5,
            "text": "Certain distinctions ",
            "relation": "ELABORATION"
        },
        {
            "id": 2,
            "parent": 1,
            "text": "made in the lexicon of one language ",
            "relation": "ELABORATION"
        },
        {
            "id": 3,
            "parent": 1,
            "text": "may be redundant ",
            "relation": "SAME-UNIT"
        },
        {
            "id": 4,
            "parent": 1,
            "text": "when translating into another language . <S>",
            "relation": "CONDITION"
        },
        {
            "id": 5,
            "parent": 6,
            "text": "We quantify redundancy among source types by the similarity of their distributions over target types . <S>",
            "relation": "BACKGROUND"
        },
        {
            "id": 6,
            "parent": 0,
            "text": "We propose a language-independent framework ",
            "relation": "ROOT"
        },
        {
            "id": 7,
            "parent": 6,
            "text": "for minimising lexical redundancy ",
            "relation": "ENABLEMENT"
        },
        {
            "id": 8,
            "parent": 7,
            "text": "that can be optimised directly from parallel text . <S>",
            "relation": "ELABORATION"
        },
        {
            "id": 9,
            "parent": 6,
            "text": "Optimisation of the source lexicon for a given target language is viewed as model selection over a set of cluster-based translation models . <S>",
            "relation": "ELABORATION"
        },
        {
            "id": 10,
            "parent": 6,
            "text": "Redundant distinctions between types may exhibit monolingual regularities , for example , inflexion patterns . <S>",
            "relation": "ELABORATION"
        },
        {
            "id": 11,
            "parent": 6,
            "text": "We define a prior over model structure ",
            "relation": "MANNER-MEANS"
        },
        {
            "id": 12,
            "parent": 11,
            "text": "using a Markov random field ",
            "relation": "ELABORATION"
        },
        {
            "id": 13,
            "parent": 11,
            "text": "and learn features over sets of monolingual types ",
            "relation": "JOINT"
        },
        {
            "id": 14,
            "parent": 13,
            "text": "that are predictive of bilingual redundancy . <S>",
            "relation": "ELABORATION"
        },
        {
            "id": 15,
            "parent": 11,
            "text": "The prior makes model selection more robust ",
            "relation": "ELABORATION"
        },
        {
            "id": 16,
            "parent": 15,
            "text": "without the need for language-specific assumptions ",
            "relation": "ELABORATION"
        },
        {
            "id": 17,
            "parent": 16,
            "text": "regarding redundancy . <S>",
            "relation": "ELABORATION"
        },
        {
            "id": 18,
            "parent": 19,
            "text": "Using these models in a phrase-based SMT system , ",
            "relation": "ELABORATION"
        },
        {
            "id": 19,
            "parent": 6,
            "text": "we show significant improvements in translation quality for certain language pairs . <S>",
            "relation": "EVALUATION"
        }
    ]
